text.tspan: Write my own C/Rust gui tool
Rust: Requires the rust tool chain to compile
Rust: May break in the future
- Must work every where (incl. under spec. systems)
- Click on blocks to open sub-diagrams
- Click on block to run custom command / open a file even on a specific line (with nvim)
- Helpers to keep blocks connected when moving them
- Select multiple blocks and move them together
- Must be easy to use with a version control
- Can include more complexe symbols / pictures / svg
- Support 100 boxes on one diagram (if there is more boxes, they would be splitted in many diagrams)
- Keyboard movements and shortcuts, hjkl for small moves, web<C-u><C-d> for jumps, WEB<C-f><C-b> to move full screens
- Can go back to previous locations with <C-O> / <C-I>
Not easy to integrate with the operating system (run custom command when clicking on blocks)
reference to font (family), design choice: One test block = one font (better consistency whithin a single block)
relative font size for small texts, design choice: some fonts results in bigger letters than others for the same size, using relative size to fix that
relative font size for medium texts,
relative font size for large texts
text processor, default if markdown, which interprets #title# ##subtitle## *bold* _underlined_ and change the font accordingly
Anchors for wires (List of Positions (X, Y) and References to struct.Connection connected to this Anchor) usually not shown but a visual presentation if displayed when in wiring mode
Use C because it still has better support on old/non-maintained systems
- Use gtk3: available everywhere, but we will only be using canvas/cairo
- Raylib is multiplatform and can run in Web Browser
Use plain text and add a diff mode
Raw source (Will be stored in a resource file with a reference counter, when no more diagrams are using it: remove it)
Annotations (Example: can be the size of a bus, the name of a signal, arrow heads, cissor...)
No good for versioning, must be stored separately
